Third, I can help them to identify their own values and priorities. When people know what is important to them, they are more likely to make a decision that aligns with their own needs and desires. I can help them to identify what matters most to them, and then use that information to guide their decision.

Fourth, I can offer support and encouragement. Decision-making can be difficult and scary, and sometimes people need someone to believe in them. I can offer words of encouragement, remind them of their strengths, and help them to build confidence in their decision.

Finally, I can be patient and understanding. Decision-making is a process, and sometimes it takes time. I can be patient with the person as they work through their decision, and not pressure them to make a quick decision.

